\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In a warm, moist environment, illness-causing bacteria can grow in high-protein, low-acid foods such as meat, fish, poultry, eggs and milk.  But there is no reason to become ill from eating or serving these foods, if they ar
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e cooked thoroughly and served or refrigerated immediately.  To prevent transferring bacteria from one food to another, use warm water and soap to wash hands, utensils and work surfaces before and after use.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 What makes chicken tender -- or tough?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Frank do\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 es his best to make Perdue chickens as tender as possible,  but there's also a lot you can do.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Don't let chicken dry out in the refrigerator;  dry chicken is tough chicken. Keep it wrapped in the package it comes in until you use it.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Avoid freezing i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
t.  When the juices inside the cells freeze, they act like little spears and they'll rupture some of the cell walls.  When you defrost the chicken, you'll lose some of the juice and the chicken will be less tender.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Cook chicken to the proper temperature,\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 using a meat thermometer or pop-up guide. Cook bone-in chicken to 180 degrees and boneless chicken to 170 degrees. Undercooked chicken will be tough and rubbery because it takes a fairly high internal temperature to soften the proteins in the muscles and
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 make them tender.  But don't overcook chicken either, because  moisture will start to steam off, and the more chicken dries out, the tougher it gets.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Keep the skin on chicken during cooking. The skin helps keep juices in, and tenderness and juiciness go \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hand in hand. I've tried this both ways, and the difference is significant. (When you cook chicken with the skin on, approximately half the fat from the skin is absorbed into the meat; if calories and cholesterol are very important to you, you might want 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o remove the skin before cooking even if it means a less tender result.)
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _When microwaving any chicken product, cover with a loose tent of waxed paper to prevent drying.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Some authorities feel strongly that you should not salt the chicken before cooking \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
because salt draws the juices out during cooking and toughens the meat.  In my experience, there is a detectable difference in tenderness between salting before cooking and salting afterwards; the chicken that I salted afterwards was slightly more tender.
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Still, I would guess that most people, myself included, wouldn't notice a big difference unless they were specifically paying attention to it.  The difference doesn't jump out at you as it does with overcooking or freezer burn.
