\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
It wasn't until the 1950s, however, that backyard barbecuing as we know it began to catch on. It may surprise you, but auto mogul Henry Ford played a major role in this$and it had nothing to do with his automobiles. Ford's contribution to backyard ba
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
rbecuing was the invention of the charcoal briquet. In the late 1920s, it was Ford who had the better idea of grinding charcoal, combining it with a starch, and re-forming it into uniform pillow shaped briquets. These charcoal briquets burned more consist
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ntly and more evenly than randomly sized and shaped lumps of charcoal.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 People immediately began using charcoal briquets for industrial purposes, but backyard grills weren't readily available yet. In the 1950s, when
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 backyard grills became widely availabl\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e, and outdoor cooking really began to take off. The combination of outdoor grills and the charcoal briquets made barbecuing so easy and reliable, that today, according to a Barbecue Industry Association survey, seven out of ten American households own a 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 b\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 arbecue grill, and we use them about 1.5 billion times a year total.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Frank and I also barbecue, but it took some learning on my part. In spite of being someone who loves to cook, before marrying Frank, I'd never barbecued. I'd never even thought to buy an\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
