\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
What I'd been missing!  Frank does own a barbecue, a nice handsome one that can manage chickenburgers for our combined eighteen children and grandchildren all at once.  I love it, because we can all be outdoors, playing volley ball or wat
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ching the young ones, with their arsenal of squirt guns, as they gang up on Frank$and the beauty of it all is that no one has to miss a moment of the fun by having to go into the kitchen to fuss with dinner.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 If you've been barbecuing for years, skip ahead\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 to the recipes.  But if you're like me and still new at it, here are some tips that can help you get uniformly good results.  The tips come from the Perdue food scientists and home economists, from Cooperative Extension and from the Barbecue Industry Ass
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ciation.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Start with a clean grill.   Removing old ashes assures good air circulation, and cleaning away any cooked-on bits of food results in better flavor and quality.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Be sure to wash everything after handling raw meat. Don't use the same plate for th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e cooked meat that you used for the uncooked meat unless you've washed it in between.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Coat grate with vegetable cooking spray, or brush with cooking oil to prevent food from sticking.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _If the basting sauce contains oil, however, do not grease the gr\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ill; too much oil causes flare-ups.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Prepare the fire a half hour or more before grilling.  For quick lighting, use a chimney starter with crumpled newspaper in the bottom and briquets or charcoal above.  Or stack the charcoal in a pyramid shape and light
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  with a liquid or electric starter, following the manufacturer's directions. Charcoal is ready for cooking when it's 80% ashy grey in daylight, glowing red at night.  This usually takes about 25 to 30 minutes.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Toss a handful of aromatic wood chips such a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s mesquite, hickory, alder, or fruitwood chips over the coals.  They'll create a whole new dimension of flavor without adding any extra calories.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Check the temperature of the fire before cooking food to prevent over- or under-cooking.  For most of the re\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
cipes in this chapter, the fire should be medium-hot with a single, even layer of coals lightly covered with grey ash. It's relatively simple to judge the temperature of a charcoal fire.  To do this, hold your hand, palm side down, at cooking height:

\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 HOT - You can hold your hand over the coals for only 2 seconds.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 MEDIUM-HOT - You can hold your hand over the coals 3 to 4 seconds.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 MEDIUM - You can hold your hand over the coals 4 to 5 seconds.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Be patient.  If the fire hasn't cooled down adequately, do\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  not be tempted to put your chicken on to cook - unless you like "blackened bird" a lot more than I do. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _If you're dieting and want to remove the chicken's skin, do so after cooking, not before.  Without some kind of covering, the chicken will dry out an\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d toughen before it finishes cooking.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Turn chicken frequently, about every 5 minutes to insure even doneness and to prevent blistering.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _If flare-ups occur, remove the food for a few moments and sprinkle water lightly over the flames, or smother them by\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 covering the grill. A friend of mine who works for a volunteer fire department keeps a laundry squirt bottle handy for flare-ups.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _To increase the heat, you can push coals together, add more coals or lower the grilling surface, or fan the fire and tap th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e ashes from the coals.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _To decrease heat, raise the cooking grid or sprinkle coals with a little water.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Cook white-meat poultry until juices run clear and the meat reaches an internal temperature of 170o to 175oF and dark meat to 180o to 185oF on a mea\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t thermometer.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Grill smaller poultry parts and Cornish game hens directly over a single layer of coals on an open grill or hibachi.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Grill whole birds and larger parts using the indirect method in a covered grill.  Place a drip pan beneath the bird; the\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 pan should be slightly larger than the bird. Fill the pan halfway with water, and surround it with a double layer of coals to provide longer, slower, oven-like cooking.  Add extra coals to the outer edge of the fire as needed to extend grilling.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _To redu\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ce the chance of overbrowning, apply tomato-based sauces or those containing sugar or other sweeteners only during last 20 to 30 minutes of grilling.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _To make breast quarters grill more quickly and evenly, cut through the wing joint to break it and bring \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 the wing closer to the grill.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Chicken should be well-done.  If you don't want to take the usual time it takes, cook your chicken partially in the microwave and then finish it on the grill.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _The basic guidelines for timing chicken on the grill are:
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Parts$Cook dark meat 30 minutes, white meat 15 minutes, basting and turning every five or so minutes.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Halves$First, grill skin side down for 5 minutes, then cook \tab covered, skin side up, 35-40 minutes.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Wings$10 minutes per side.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Whole$(about 3 and 1/2\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  pounds...About 1 and 1/4 to 1 and 1/2 hours in a covered grill, 1 and 1/2 to 2 hours on rotisserie.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Use tongs rather than a fork to turn food gently without losing juices.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _If you plan to use marinade as a sauce to be served with chicken during the mea\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
l, be sure to cook it before using.  You want to avoid the cross-contamination that can come from contact with the uncooked chicken. Temperatures over 140 degrees will destroy any microbes.
