he event. Or you've got a busy week coming up and you want to do better by your family than just giving them calorie-laden, greasy take-out food. Or you're having house guests, and you want to spend the time with them instead of in the kitchen.  Or maybe 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 here's only one or two of you at home, and you've discovered that it's simpler to make a recipe for four and freeze part of it for use later.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In my own case, my freezer is always full.  One reason is that Frank often invites three or four people the last \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
minute, and it helps to have emergency food on hand. Equally often, after I've made a meal, he'll call at 6:00 p.m. and tell me that we're eating out with one of the poultry distributors or suppliers, and I end up freezing what I've just cooked.  As I wra
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  the food in foil and wedge it into the freezer, I remind myself, "This meal isn't going to waste, it's a head start on a future meal."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 When you know the principles for successful freezing$and I'll get to them in a moment$you can freeze just about any of \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
the recipes in this cookbook. The recipes in this chapter are different from the rest because they not only can be cooked ahead, often they  should be cooked ahead.  Some of them require marination, others improve with age, and still others adapt so well 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
o cooking the day before that they belong in this chapter. Use this chapter for recipes to use when you want to cook a day or so ahead of time, and also, use it for tips on how to freeze foods successfully.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 There are just a few principles needed to master\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  the technique of cooking ahead, and once you know them, you'll have faster, better-tasting, healthier and safer meals to show for it.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _The biggest boon to food preparation ahead is the freezer.  Everything freezes from the point of view of food safety, b\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ut there's a lot of variation in palatability. For best flavor and texture, don't freeze the following foods in your home freezer:
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Milk products $ they'll curdle.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Boiled eggs $  the whites get watery.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Custards $ they'll lose texture, get lumpy.  
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Mayonnaise $ it may separate.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Most foods that you fry at home (except french fries and onions) $ they can get an unattractive "warmed-over" taste.  It's actually the fats turning slightly rancid.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Cooked potatoes $ they darken and get an unattracti\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ve texture. (If you're going to freeze stew, add cooked potatoes later on when you're reheating the stew.)  
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Fresh greens, celery, and carrots $ they get limp. 
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Fresh tomatoes $  their high water content causes them to collapse when thawed. (However,\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  you can freeze tomatoes if you're going to use them in a cooked form, such as in a pasta sauce.)
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Gravy $ the fat will separate out and puddle.  (If you must freeze gravy, cut way back on the fat when you're making the gravy, and stir constantly when yo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
u're reheating it so as to keep the fat from separating.)
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Heavily spiced foods $ most herbs, salts, onions, fade away, but garlic and cloves will seem more intense.   Pepper has a tendency to turn bitter. Curry takes on a musty flavor.  
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Synthetic fl\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 avors $ use real vanilla rather than synthetic because synthetic vanilla can have an off-flavor after freezing.
\par 
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Highly salted foods $ salt tends to attract moisture and uneven freezing may result because salt slows down the freezing process.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 _Even if\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 you're freezing food for only a couple of days, be careful of packaging. Air that's in the package will affect the color, flavor and texture.  The container should be air tight, or the food will get freezer burn and lose nutritional value, and palatabili
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 y.
