\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 George and Martha Washington made much of Christmas.  They had been married on the twelfth night of Christmas in 1759, and from that year forward\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 they tried to be together for the holidays.  (The exceptions were such occasions as Christmas 1776, when General Washington was busy crossing the Delaware.)
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0     Two of the food specialists at Perdue are history buffs as well, an they put together for Fran\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
k a Christmas menu based on "receipts" (as recipes were once called) for dishes that might have been enjoyed at Christmas dinner, two hundred years ago.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 As they pointed out, even basic food supplies were very different two centuries ago.  American waters \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
were so abundant with crabs, oysters, shrimp and clams, that inventive cooks tossed them into soups and spreads, baked them "potted," "scalloped" or in loaves, and used them lavishly in sauces and stuffings.  The oyster stuffing included in this menu is b
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
sed on a specialty of George Washington's mother.  She may have served it with passenger pigeon $common fare in those days.  Although this wild bird is extinct today, Cornish game hens make tasty, tender, modern substitutes.  And it is far easier to "bag 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  brace" or two of Cornish hens at the local supermarket than to stalk dinner in the wild.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Early Americans weren't partial to vegetables.  They tended to overcook and under season them, then serve them up as a "mess of pease".  But old-time cooks did make \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
wonderful vegetable puddings and were superb at pickling and preserving their vegetables and fruits to serve all winter long.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 From the beginning, American settlers distilled spirits.  Even the stern Pilgrims (who considered the celebration of Christmas pa\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
gan) drank wine and cider for their health.  After a festive holiday meal, most of our founding fathers probably enjoyed a few rounds of Madeira or Port.  But Thomas Jefferson's favorite holiday drink was a spicy mixture of hot ale and rum, so heat produc
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ng it was called "a yard of flannel".  Frothy syllabub was thought to be suitable for everyone, even women and children, and this rich drink was a delicious accompaniment to sweetmeats, stewed fruit, cakes or pies.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Though few would wish to return to cooki\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ng at the hearth and beehive oven, if you're smitten by the romance of the past, try serving special guests a Christmas dinner Martha Washington-style.
